folder: Utopia Parkway & Union Turnpike, Queens, NY
text:
Utopia Parkway (Fresh Meadow Road), west side between Union Turnpike and Seventy-sixth Ave., showing is a set of four views the Van Siclen farm, farmhouse and outbuildings. It belonged to J., in 1860; C.K., in 1873; C., in 1891; and Garrett Van Sicklen in 1909. The place was demolished in November 1933 by fire.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Union Turnpike & Utopia Parkway, Queens, NY
text:
Union Turnpike, at the N.W. corner of Utopia Parkway, showing the abandoned Van Siclen house. In 1873 the land was owned by C. Van Siclen, comprising 124 acres on both sides of Union Turnpike, then called Union Avenue, the eastern limit of which was Utopia Parkway, then called Fresh meadow Road. In 1909, however, the farm was comprised only of 49 acres and was owned by Garrett Van Sicklen.
P.L. Sperr March 31, 1927
title: Queens: Union Turnpike - Utopia Parkway

folder: Utopia Parkway & Union Turnpike, Queens, NY
text:
Utopia Parkway, east side, north from Union Turnpike, showing the farm which was owned by the Schleider family from 1873 to 1909. Beyond the farmhouse is Public School 26, the old Black Stump District School of 1873. This whole area later became a modern residential district.
P.L. Sperr March 31, 1927
